GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 870
Short Title: Sedimentation Act & Other Env.'l Changes. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Brody, Adams, N. Jackson, and Zenger (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Housing and Development, if favorable, Finance, if favorable, Rules, Calendar,
and Operations of the House
April 10, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO AMEND SEDIMENTATION CONTROL PERMITTING REQUIREMENTS, TO
3 ESTABLISH NEW REQUIREMENTS FOR MEMORANDUMS OF AGREEMENT
4 BETWEEN THE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND THE
5 UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY, AND TO MAKE
6 OTHER CHANGES TO THE ADMINISTRATION OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROGRAMS
7 IN NORTH CAROLINA.
8 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
9
10 MEMORANDUM OF AGREEMENTS BETWEEN DEQ AND USEPA TO REQUIRE
11 GENERAL ASSEMBLY APPROVAL
12 SECTION 1.(a) Article 7 of Chapter 143B of the General Statutes is amended by
13 adding a new section to read:
14 "§ 143B-279.4B. Requirements for Department administration of federally delegated
15 environmental programs.
16 All memorandums of agreement between the United States Environmental Protection
17 Agency and the Department of Environmental Quality, the Environmental Management
18 Commission, the Coastal Resources Commission, the Sedimentation Control Commission, and
19 any other board or commission charged under the State's statutes with implementation of State
20 or federal environmental law shall, prior to execution, require approval of the General Assembly
21 by majority vote of the Senate and the House of Representatives. The Governor shall transmit
22 any proposed memorandums of agreements of this nature, or modifications to such agreements,
23 to the presiding officers of the Senate and the House of Representatives for confirmation by joint
24 resolution. Implementation of the terms of such agreements shall be prohibited absent
25 confirmation by the General Assembly."
26 SECTION 1.(b) G.S. 143B-279.4B, as enacted by subsection (a) of this section, shall
27 apply to memorandums of agreement, or modifications to such agreements, proposed for
28 execution on or after the effective date of this act.
29
30 DEQ TO INITIATE DISCUSSIONS WITH USEPA TO REVISE MEMORANDUM OF
31 AGREEMENT(S) GOVERNING IMPLEMENTATION OF SEDIMENTATION
32 REQUIREMENTS IN THE STATE
33 SECTION 2. No later than October 1, 2025, the Department of Environmental
34 Quality shall notify the United States Environmental Protection Agency (USEPA) of its intent to
*H870-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 initiate discussions to revise the National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System Memorandum
2 of Agreement between the State of North Carolina and USEPA Region 4, and any other
3 agreement with USEPA, that governs the State's Sedimentation Pollution Control Act of 1973
4 (Act), and its implementation of NPDES General Permit NCG010000 (NCG01) to streamline the
5 regulatory requirements of the Act and NCG01 for the purpose of eliminating program
6 redundancies to minimize (i) unnecessary costs to, and duplication of efforts by, persons
7 initiating land-disturbing activities, (ii) unnecessary delays in project development, and (iii)
8 inefficient use of Department personnel and staff of local governments that administer delegated
9 erosion and sedimentation control programs. The Speaker of the House of Representatives and
10 the President Pro Tempore of the Senate may each appoint a person to participate in the
11 discussions, and the Department shall provide notice of and access to all discussions and
12 materials related to the negotiations. The appointees shall report to the Speaker of the House of
13 Representatives and the President Pro Tempore of the Senate on the progress and results of the
14 discussions. The Department shall report to the Environmental Policy Council on the status of
15 their activities pursuant to this section quarterly, beginning January 1, 2026, until such time as
16 the General Assembly repeals this reporting requirement.
17
18 DEQ TO REQUEST THAT USEPA CONSULT DEQ ON PROPOSED CHANGES TO
19 ALL APPLICABLE FEDERAL REGULATIONS PRIOR TO NOTICE OF SAME IN
20 THE FEDERAL REGISTER
21 SECTION 3. No later than October 1, 2025, the Department of Environmental
22 Quality shall request that the United States Environmental Protection Agency (USEPA) consult
23 with the Department on any proposed changes to federal regulations that would impact the State's
24 administration of federal environmental programs in North Carolina, prior to the USEPA's notice
25 of such proposed changes in the Federal Register, so that the State may have opportunity for
26 meaningful collaborative input on development of regulations that it may be charged with
27 administering. The Department shall report to the Environmental Policy Council on the status of
28 their activities pursuant to this section quarterly, beginning January 1, 2026, until such time as
29 the General Assembly repeals this reporting requirement.
30
31 DEQ TO PROVIDE COPIES OF AGREEMENTS WITH USEPA AND ASSOCIATED
32 FUNDING INFORMATION
33 SECTION 4. No later than October 1, 2025, the Department of Environmental
34 Quality shall submit copies of any agreements executed between the Department and the United
35 States Environmental Protection Agency that govern the State's administration of programs under
36 the Clean Water Act to the House Local Government – Land Use, Planning and Development
37 Committee. In addition, the Department shall provide information to the Committee on:
38 (1) Any federal funds received by the State in connection with the State's
39 administration of such programs, and all federal requirements for receipt of
40 such funds; and
41 (2) The adequacy of funding from all sources to fully implement the requirements
42 of such agreements.
43
44 SEVERABILITY CLAUSE
45 SECTION 5. If any section or provision of this act is declared unconstitutional or
46 invalid by the courts, it does not affect the validity of this act as a whole or any part other than
47 the part declared to be unconstitutional or invalid.
48
49 EFFECTIVE DATE
50 SECTION 6. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
51 law.
